<h2>Defining Variables</h2>

<p>
    Here, data_type must be a valid C# data type including char, int, float, double, or<br />
    any user-defined data type, and variable_list may consist of one or more identifier<br />
    names separated by commas.
</p>

<p>Some valid variable definitions are shown here:</p>

<p>
    int i, j, k; <br />
    char c, ch; <br />
    float f, salary;<br />
    double d;
    string s;
</p>

<h2>Initializing Variables</h2>

<p>
    Variables are initialized (assigned a value) with an equal sign followed by a constant expression.<br />
    The general form of initialization is:
</p>

<p>variable_name = value;</p>
<p>int i = 10;</p>
<p>double = 10.5</p>

<h2>Constants</h2>
<p>
    The constants refer to fixed values that the program may not alter during its execution. These fixed values <br />
    are also called literals. Constants can be of any of the basic data types like an integer constant, a floating <br/>
    constant, a character constant, or a string literal. There are also enumeration constants as well.
</p>

<h2>Defining Constants</h2>

<p>Constants are defined using the const keyword. Syntax for defining a constant is:</p>

<p>const double pi = 3.14159;  </p>

